      "span_text": "The intact cag PAI of H. pylori plays a significant role in the pathogenesis of chronic gastritis in humans because the cag PAI is associated with increased chemokine expression and greater inflammation in gastric mucosal specimens. After the CagA protein is injected into the host cell cytoplasm through the type IV secretory system, the EPIYA motif of CagA is tyrosine-phosphorylated by host Src kinases, and the phosphorylated protein subsequently alters the gastric epithelial morphology."
